# 1. Priliminary Steps to Start using Astropy within jupyter-lab: 

# In order for Jupyter-lab to recognize Astropy I need to creating a separate Python environment specifically for Jupyter Lab and 
# install Astropy within that environment. Obviosly this only needs to be done once. This will ensure that Jupyter Lab is using a consistent and compatible version of Astropy.
# This is what the code to do that looks like:

# Install the virtualenv package using pip:
pip install virtualenv

# Create a virtual environment for Jupyter Lab:
virtualenv jupyterlab-env

# Activate the virtual environment:
source jupyterlab-env/bin/activate

# Install Astropy within the virtual environment:
pip install astropy

# Launch Jupyter Lab using the virtual environment (the ~/jupyterlab is indicating that all jupyter notes are to be saved in here so if you don't have that folder create it in the home folder first):
jupyter-lab --notebook-dir=~/jupyterlab

# Now this time when I execute some astropy command in the jupyter note, it does indeed recognize astropy.
# So the Main takeaway from this was that I need to start using jupyter-lab from within the same environment as the one astropy is installed in and this env should be
# broughut up everytime I wantto use that:
# first in terminal go to the directory where jupyterlab-env is located and then:

source jupyterlab-env/bin/activate
